# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cloud-security-posture
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] A **cloud access security broker** (**CASB**) (sometimes pronounced cas-bee) is on-premises or cloud based software that sits between cloud service users and cloud applications, and monitors all activity and enforces security policies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] A CASB can offer services such as monitoring user activity, warning administrators about potentially hazardous actions, enforcing security policy compliance, and automatically preventing malware.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] CASBs deliver security and management features.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Broadly speaking, "security" is the prevention of high-risk events, whilst "management" is the monitoring and mitigation of high-risk events.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] CASBs that deliver security must be in the path of data access, between the user and the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Architecturally, this might be achieved with proxy agents on each end-point device, or in agentless fashion without configuration on each device.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Agentless CASBs allow for rapid deployment and deliver security on both company-managed and unmanaged BYOD devices.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Agentless CASB also respect user privacy, inspecting only corporate data.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Agent-based CASBs are difficult to deploy and effective only on devices that are managed by the corporation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-access-security-broker] Agent-based CASBs typically inspect both corporate and personal data.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-workload-protection-platform] A **cloud workload protection platform (CWPP)** is a computer security software aimed at securing (potentially virtual) computer machines.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-workload-protection-platform] CWPPs are usually agent-based, meaning that a software agent is running permanently within the machine to be protected, collecting security-relevant data and events and sending those to a cloud-based service.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-workload-protection-platform] The cloud-based service monitors all the machines under its supervision, derives alerts and notifies users about corresponding potential security threats.
[src:cloud-security-posture/cloud-workload-protection-platform] Gartner maintains a list of CWPP vendor-based solutions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A **data center** is a facility used to house computer systems and associated components, such as telecommunications and storage systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers are critical infrastructure for the storage and processing of information, and they support the global financial system, cloud services, machine learning, and artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers vary widely in terms of size, power and water requirements, and overall structure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Hyperscale and colocation facilities collectively account for approximately 74% of U.S. server energy consumption as of 2023, a share that has grown significantly over the past decade as workloads have migrated away from enterprise on-premises infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Since IT operations are crucial for business continuity, a data center generally includes redundant or backup components.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Other important design considerations are power supply, network infrastructure, environmental controls (e.g., cooling, fire suppression), and various measures for physical and data security.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Large data centers operate at an industrial scale, requiring significant energy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Estimated global data center electricity consumption in 2024 was around 415 terawatt hours (TWh), or about 1.5% of global electricity demand.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The International Energy Agency (IEA) projects that data center electricity consumption could double by 2030.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of data center infrastructure has prompted regulatory debates in multiple jurisdictions regarding tax incentives, electricity grid impacts, water consumption, and compatibility with state and national climate commitments.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Rapid growth of the AI industry is leading to strain on electric grids and increased electricity costs for consumers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This in turn has drawn growing opposition to new data centers from local people who would bear the burdens of social and environmental impacts, such as energy and water use, while faraway actors and institutions would receive the projects' benefits.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These opposition movements have materialized especially in parts of Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Billions of dollars in projects were halted or delayed by data center resistances in the U.S. between May 2024 and June 2025.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers are usually classified according to their ownership model, scale, and intended use.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, these classifications are not mutually exclusive from each other, and they may overlap depending on the operational structure and service model of the particular data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Enterprise data centers are owned and operated by a single organization for their own internal information technology (IT) needs, rather than for commercial hosting of other companies' data.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] They used to be essential infrastructures; as in 2014, enterprise data centers accounted for over 60% of the U.S. server energy consumption, but this share fell sharply to about 10% by 2023 as workloads migrated to hyperscale and colocation facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Energy efficiency at an enterprise data center tends to be significantly lower than at hyperscale facilities due to its cooling, which can account for over 30% of electricity consumption at enterprise sites, compared to roughly 7% at efficient hyperscale data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The shift away from enterprise facilities toward cloud and colocation infrastructure is one of the defining structural trends of the previous decade.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Colocation centers provide shared physical infrastructure, such as power, cooling, space, etc., to multiple tenants who lease space rather than building their own facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Colocation data centers reduce expenditure for organizations while enabling operators to achieve economies of scale in power procurement and cooling efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Some of the largest data centers in the world are colocation centers, and this category accounted for about 22% of worldwide data center capacity as of 2024, making them the second-largest category by capacity after hyperscale facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Major colocation providers include Equinix, Switch, COPT, and Digital Realty, which operate facilities across multiple continents.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Hyperscale data centers are large-scale facilities, typically exceeding 100 megawatts of power capacity, designed to support massive, scalable computing workloads for cloud services, AI training, and large-scale data processing.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] By the end of 2024, there were 1,136 operational hyperscale data centers globally, a figure that doubled over the previous five years, with the U.S. accounting for approximately 54% of total hyperscale capacity.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In particular, the three largest operators, Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud, collectively account for approximately 59% of all hyperscale data center capacity globally.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As a growing trend, hyperscale data centers represented about 41% of worldwide data center capacity in 2024 and are projected to exceed 60% by 2029 as enterprise on-premises infrastructure continues to decline.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Moreover, as artificial intelligence (AI) is becoming widely used, AI data centers are being built more rapidly, and they can consume as much electricity as 100,000 households, more than conventional data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Since 2024, there has been widespread grassroots Opposition to AI Data Centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Edge data centers are smaller facilities, typically ranging from 1 to 10 megawatts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] They are positioned closer to end users or data sources to reduce network latency and support real-time applications, such as autonomous vehicles, industrial automation, and content delivery.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Unlike hyperscale data centers, edge data centers are intentionally distributed across many locations rather than consolidated, with deployments occurring in urban areas, cell tower sites, as well as industrial locations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The growth of edge computing infrastructure has been tied to the expansion of 5G wireless networks and the increasing use of Internet of Things (IoT) devices, which generate data that is more efficiently processed near its source than transmitted to a centralized data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Micro data centers (MDCs) are access-level data centers that are smaller in size than traditional data centers but provide the same features.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] They are typically located near the data source to reduce communication delays, as their small size allows several MDCs to be spread out over a wide area.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] MDCs are suited to user-facing, front end applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] They are commonly used in edge computing and other areas where low latency data processing is needed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Modularity and flexibility are key elements in allowing a data center to grow and change over time.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data center modules are pre-engineered, standardized building blocks that can be configured and moved as needed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A modular data center may consist of data center equipment contained within shipping containers or similar portable containers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Components of the data center can be prefabricated and standardized, which facilitates moving if needed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These modular data centers are useful for IT disaster recovery.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Mobile data centers are also used to move large quantities of data, by physically transporting the hardware that contains it, and in cryptocurrency mining, where fleets of mobile data centers are transported to take advantage of cheaper sources of energy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers have their roots in the huge computer rooms of the 1940s, typified by the Electronic Numerical Integrator and Computer (ENIAC), one of the earliest examples of a data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Early computer systems were complex to operate and maintain, and required a special environment in which to operate.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Many cables were necessary to connect all of the components, and methods to accommodate and organize these were devised such as standard racks to mount equipment, raised floors, and cable trays (installed overhead or under the elevated floor).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A single mainframe required a great deal of power and had to be cooled to avoid overheating.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Security became important – computers were expensive, and were often used for government and military purposes.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As such, basic design guidelines for controlling access to the computer room were devised.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] During the microcomputer industry boom of the 1980s, computers started to be deployed everywhere, in many cases with little or no care about operating requirements.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, as information technology (IT) operations started to grow in complexity, organizations grew aware of the need to control IT resources.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The availability of inexpensive networking equipment, coupled with new standards for the network structured cabling, made it possible to use a hierarchical design that put servers in a specific room inside the company.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The use of the term *data center*, as applied to specially designed computer rooms, started to gain popular recognition about this time.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] During the dot-com bubble (1997–2000), there was a boom in data center construction because companies needed fast Internet connectivity and non-stop operation to establish their Internet presence.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The global data center market saw steady growth in the 2010s, with a notable acceleration in the latter half of the decade.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] According to Gartner, worldwide data center infrastructure spending reached $200 billion in 2021, representing a 6% increase from 2020 despite economic challenges posed by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2024, global energy consumption from data centers was 620 TWh, with 80% of that consumption concentrated in the U.S., China, and the United Kingdom.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Colocation centers were the most common category worldwide, with 4,799 colocation centers in 127 countries.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In that year, the largest data center in the world was Citadel, owned by Switch, at the Tahoe Reno Industrial Center in Reno, Nevada, occupying 7.2 million square feet.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Growth of the data center industry has prompted local resistance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A 2023 survey found social mobilizations against the industry in Europe, the U.S., and South America.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These movements expressed concern about the centers' energy and water use, pollution, and impact on agriculture or the landscape.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A 2026 poll by *Politico* suggested that resistance to growth of the industry would make candidates' stance on data centers a significant issue for voters in the U.S.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The U.S. hosted 5,381 data centers in March 2024, the highest number of any country worldwide, accounting for 40% of the global market in 2023.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As of 2023, about 80% of U.S. data center load was concentrated in 15 states, led by Virginia and Texas.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As of 2025, roughly one third of America's data centers were in three states: Virginia (643), Texas (395), and California (319).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The largest concentration of data centers in the world is in Northern Virginia, with over 250 facilities in the region.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2025, Georgia was the fastest growing data center hub in the U.S., having enacted several state tax exemptions for the industry and hosting between 100 and 150 centers in the state.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Local governments have responded to the growing industry in Georgia with a variety of local ordinances to guide permitting of these facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The consultancy firm McKinsey & Co., projected U.S. demand to double to 35 gigawatts (GW) by 2030, up from 17 GW in 2022.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A study published by the Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI) in May 2024 estimated that data centers could consume between 4.6% and 9.1% of the country's electricity generation by 2030.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] GDP growth was only 0.1% without the investments in data centers for artificial intelligence.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers house critical computing resources in a controlled environment and must generally operate with very high availability.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Key design elements include providing power for the equipment, temperature and humidity control, cabling, fire safety, and security.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For this reason, a data center has to offer a secure environment that minimizes the chances of a security breach.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Industry research company International Data Corporation (IDC) puts the average age of a data center at nine years old.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Gartner, another research company, says data centers older than seven years are obsolete.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The growth in data (163 zettabytes by 2025) is one factor driving the need for data centers to modernize.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Rapid obsolescence of data center equipment was a concern by at least 2007, and in 2011, Uptime Institute was concerned about aging equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The topology proposed in this document is intended to be applicable to any size data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Telcordia GR-3160, *NEBS Requirements for Telecommunications Data Center Equipment and Spaces*, provides guidelines for data center spaces within telecommunications networks, and environmental requirements for the equipment intended for installation in those spaces.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These criteria were developed jointly by Telcordia and industry representatives.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] They may be applied to data center spaces housing data processing or IT equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power supplies, either back up or continuous onsite power, consist of one or more uninterruptible power supplies, battery banks, diesel, gas turbine, and/or gas engine generating sets.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Greater primary fuel energy efficiency can be achieved with the use of cogeneration technology, generating electricity, heating, and cooling onsite.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] To prevent single points of failure, all elements of the electrical systems, including backup systems, are typically given redundant copies, and critical servers are connected to both the *A-side* and *B-side* power feeds.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This arrangement is often made to achieve N+1 redundancy in the systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Static transfer switches are sometimes used to ensure instantaneous switchover from one supply to the other in the event of a power failure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Options for low-voltage cable routing might include data cabling that is routed through overhead cable trays; raised floor cabling, both for security reasons and to avoid the extra cost of cooling systems over the racks; and anti-static tiles for flooring, especially in low-cost data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Maintaining suitable temperature and humidity levels is critical to preventing equipment damage caused by overheating.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Overheating can cause components (usually the silicon or copper of the wires or circuits) to melt, causing loose connections and fire hazards.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Typical temperature control methods include air conditioning and indirect cooling, such as the use of outside air, indirect evaporative cooling units, and seawater cooling.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Airflow management is the practice of achieving data center cooling efficiency by preventing the recirculation of hot exhaust air and by reducing bypass airflow.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Common approaches include hot-aisle/cold-aisle containment and the deployment of in-row cooling units, which position cooling directly between server racks to intercept exhaust heat before it mixes with room air.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Humidity control prevents moisture and related issues.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For example, excess humidity can cause dust to adhere more readily to fan blades and heat sinks, impeding air cooling and leading to higher temperatures.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Cold aisle containment is done by exposing the rear of equipment racks, while the fronts of the servers are enclosed with doors and covers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This is similar to how large-scale food companies refrigerate and store products.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Computer cabinets/server farms are often organized for containment of hot/cold aisles.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Proper air duct placement prevents cold and hot air from mixing.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Rows of cabinets are paired to face each other so the cool and hot air intakes and exhausts do not mix air, which would severely reduce cooling efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Alternatively, a range of underfloor panels can create efficient cold air pathways directed to the raised-floor vented tiles.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Either the cold aisle or the hot aisle can be contained.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Another option is fitting cabinets with vertical exhaust duct chimneys.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Hot exhaust pipes/vents/ducts can direct the air into a plenum space above a dropped ceiling and back to the cooling units or to outside vents.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] With this configuration, traditional hot/cold aisle configuration is not required.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers feature fire protection systems, including passive and active design elements, as well as implementation of fire prevention programs in operations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Smoke detectors are usually installed to provide early warning of a fire.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Although the main room usually does not allow wet pipe-based systems due to the fragile nature of circuit boards, there are systems that can be used in the rest of the facility or in cold/hot aisle air circulation systems that are closed systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These include sprinkler systems and misting, the latter of which uses high pressure to create extremely small water droplets and can be used in sensitive rooms due to the nature of the droplets.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, there are other means to put out fires, especially in Sensitive areas, usually using gaseous fire suppression, of which Halon gas was the most popular, until the negative effects of producing and using it were discovered.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Physical access to data centers is usually restricted.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Layered security often starts with fencing, bollards, and mantraps.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Video camera surveillance and permanent security guards are almost always present if the data center is large or contains sensitive information.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Fingerprint recognition is starting to become commonplace.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Logging access is required by some data protection regulations; some organizations tightly link this to access control systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Multiple log entries can occur at the main entrance, entrances to internal rooms, and at equipment cabinets.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Access control at cabinets can be integrated with intelligent power distribution units, so locks are networked through the same appliance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data center transformation takes a step-by-step approach through integrated projects carried out over time.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This differs from a traditional method of data center upgrades, which takes a serial and siloed approach.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Typical projects within a data center transformation initiative include standardization/consolidation, virtualization, automation, and security.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data center consolidation consists of reducing the number of data centers and avoiding *server sprawl* (both physical and virtual), which often includes replacing aging data center equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This process is aided by standardization, which makes these systems follow a uniform set of configurations to simplify and improve efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Automating tasks such as provisioning, configuration, patching, release management, and compliance are other ways in which data centers can be upgraded.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] These changes are needed not just when facing fewer skilled IT workers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Lastly, security initiatives integrate the protection of virtual systems with existing security for physical infrastructures.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The first raised floor computer room was made by IBM in 1956 to allow access for wiring.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] During the 1970s, raised floors became more common because they allow cool air to circulate more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A raised floor standards guide (GR-2930) was developed by Telcordia Technologies, a subsidiary of Ericsson.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The "lights-out" data center, also known as a darkened or dark data center, is a data center that has largely eliminated the need for direct access by personnel, except under extraordinary circumstances.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Due to the lack of need for staff to enter the data center, it can be operated without lighting.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] All of the devices are accessed and managed by remote systems, with automation programs used to perform unattended operations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In addition to the energy savings, reduction in staffing costs, and the ability to locate the site further from population centers, implementing a lights-out data center also reduces the threat of malicious attacks upon the infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulations require monitoring of noise levels inside data centers if noise exceeds 85 decibels.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The average noise level in server areas of a data center may reach as high as 92–96 dB(A).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Residents living near data centers have described the sound as "a high-pitched whirring noise 24/7", saying "It's like being on a tarmac with an airplane engine running constantly ...
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] External sources of noise include HVAC (heating, ventilation, and air conditioning) equipment and energy generators.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Location factors include proximity to power grids, telecommunications infrastructure, networking services, transportation lines, and emergency services.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Other considerations should include flight paths, neighboring power drains, geological risks, and climate (associated with cooling costs).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Local political considerations, such as availability of subsidies and lack of opposition, are also important factors in locating data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Various metrics exist to measure the data-availability that results from data-center availability beyond 95% uptime, with the top of the scale counting how many *nines* can be placed after *99%*.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The costs of avoiding downtime should not exceed the cost of the downtime itself.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Dynamic infrastructure provides the ability to intelligently, automatically, and securely move workloads within a data center anytime, anywhere, for migrations, provisioning, to enhance performance, or build co-location facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] It also facilitates performing routine maintenance on either physical or virtual systems, all while minimizing interruption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A related concept is Composable Infrastructure, which allows for the dynamic reconfiguration of the available resources to suit needs, only when needed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Communications in modern data centers are most often based on networks running the Internet protocol suite.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers contain a set of routers and switches that transport traffic between the servers and to the outside world, which are connected according to the data center network architecture.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Redundancy of the internet connection is often provided by using two or more upstream service providers (see Multihoming).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Some of the servers at a data center are used for running the basic internet and intranet services needed by internal users in the organization, e.g., e-mail servers, proxy servers, and DNS servers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Network security elements are also usually deployed: firewalls, VPN gateways, intrusion detection systems, and so on.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Also common are monitoring systems for the network and some of the applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Additional off-site monitoring systems are also typical, in case of a failure of communications inside the data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Energy consumption and the environmental impacts it creates are a central issue for data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power draw ranges from a few kilowatts (kW) for small server racks to several tens of megawatts (MW) for large facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Modern hyperscale data centers can exhibit power densities exceeding 100 times those of conventional office buildings, primarily due to the high concentration of servers and cooling systems required to manage continuous digital workloads.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For higher power density facilities, electricity costs are a dominant operating expense and account for over 10% of the total cost of ownership (TCO) of a data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As of 2024, data centers in the U.S. are primarily powered by natural gas, which supplies 40% of their electricity (with renewable energy at 24%, nuclear at about 20%, and coal at about 15%).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The *Associated Press* reported that electricity for AI data centers in the U.S. would likely come from natural gas or oil, as companies prefer using currently available power plants, which primarily use fossil fuels.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Fossil energy is also often cheaper in locations where data centers are developed, and experts believe that energy demands from generative AI and data centers would be difficult to fulfill with renewable energy alone.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Some companies such as Google, Amazon, and Meta have expressed interest in nuclear power for their data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As of 2020, according to the IEA, solar photovoltaic-generated electricity is at its lowest cost in history.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Other data centers, including xAI's Colossus, OpenAI's Stargate, and Meta's Prometheus use their own off-grid natural gas plants.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Electric vehicle and lithium-ion batteries have also been used for powering data centers, including for Colossus.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power utility companies make upgrades to their infrastructure to handle demands of new data centers, and the price for these changes typically falls on residential or smaller commercial consumers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2025, the Mountain Valley Pipeline announced plans to expand its capacity by 25% to meet energy needs for data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In December 2025, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (FERC) published a unanimous order allowing data centers in the U.S. to have a direct connection with power plants.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] United States Secretary of Energy Chris Wright expressed support for un-retiring coal plants to power AI data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Electricity demands from AI data centers have slowed or reversed the retirement of peaking power plants in the U.S.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For example, in 2025, Southern Company announced that energy use from data centers would prevent the company from retiring coal-fired power plants as it had earlier promised.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In Nevada, the Desert Research Institute (DRI) calculated that 35% of the state's energy production could go to data centers by the year 2030 if all projects planned in the state as of 2026 are completed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] DRI also stated, in areas where there are clusters of data centers, local consumers may end up paying the extra cost of expanding infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2024, data centers were estimated to account for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption (approximately 415 TWh) and around 1% of greenhouse gas emissions according to U.S.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, the rapid expansion is causing projections to rise sharply.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Due to accelerated demand from AI, data center's global electricity consumption is projected to more than double to around 945 TWh by 2030 in the IEA's base-case scenario, which represents just under 3% of 2030 total global electricity consumption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This growing electricity demand, much of which is still generated by fossil fuels, increases the potential environmental impacts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In addition to operational energy demand, embodied life cycle emissions should be considered, which include the extraction, manufacturing, transportation, and recycling or disposal of materials used in the construction of facilities and hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Global data center carbon dioxide emissions are projected to rise from an estimated 220 million tonnes in 2024 to 300–320 million tonnes by 2035.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google and Microsoft each consumed more power than over 100 countries.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As a result, there is increasing industry pressure for decarbonization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Companies are pursuing direct clean energy agreements, such as Tencent who has pledged to be carbon neutral by 2030, and Microsoft's 2024 agreement to re-open the Three Mile Island nuclear power plant to provide 100% of the electric power for its AI data centers for 20 years.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The most commonly used energy efficiency metric for data centers is power usage effectiveness (PUE), calculated as the ratio of total power entering the data center divided by the power used by IT equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] PUE measures the percentage of power used by overhead devices (cooling, lighting, etc.).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The average U.S. data center has a PUE of 2.0, meaning two watts of total power (overhead + IT equipment) for every watt delivered to IT equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] State-of-the-art data centers are estimated to have a PUE of roughly 1.2.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Google publishes quarterly efficiency metrics from its data centers in operation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] PUEs of as low as 1.01 have been achieved with two-phase immersion cooling.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The EPA has an Energy Star rating for standalone or large data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] To qualify for the ecolabel, a data center must be within the top quartile in energy efficiency of all reported facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The Energy Efficiency Improvement Act of 2015 (U.S.) requires federal facilities—including data centers—to operate more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] California's Title 24 (2014) of the California Code of Regulations mandates that every newly constructed data center must have some form of airflow containment in place to optimize energy efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The European Union (EU) also has a similar initiative: EU Code of Conduct for Data Centres.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Efficiency improvements and renewable energy integration are helping offset some emissions, but fossil fuels remain a major electricity source for data center operations worldwide.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2011, server racks in data centers were designed for more than 25 kW, and the typical server was estimated to waste about 30% of the electricity it consumed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The energy demand for information storage systems is also rising.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A high-availability data center is estimated to have a 1 MW demand and consume $20 million in electricity over its lifetime, with cooling representing 35% to 45% of the data center's total cost of ownership.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Calculations show that in two years, the cost of powering and cooling a server could be equal to the cost of purchasing the server hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Research in 2018 showed that a substantial amount of energy could still be conserved by optimizing IT refresh rates and increasing server use.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Research for optimizing task scheduling is also underway, with researchers looking to implement energy-efficient scheduling algorithms that could reduce energy consumption by anywhere between 6% and 44%.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2011, Facebook, Rackspace, and others founded the Open Compute Project (OCP) to develop and publish open standards for greener data center computing technologies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As part of the project, Facebook published the designs of its server, which it had built for its first dedicated data center in Prineville.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Making servers taller left space for more effective heat sinks and enabled the use of fans that moved more air with less energy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] By not buying commercial off-the-shelf servers, energy consumption due to unnecessary expansion slots on the motherboard and unneeded components, such as a graphics card, was also saved.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2016, Google joined the project and published the designs of its 48V DC shallow data center rack.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This design had long been part of Google data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] By eliminating the multiple transformers usually deployed in data centers, Google had achieved a 30% increase in energy efficiency.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2017, sales for data center hardware built to OCP designs topped $1.2 billion and are expected to reach $6 billion by 2021.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power is the largest recurring cost to the user of a data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2008, the ASHRAE recommended a temperature range of 64.4 °F (18.0 °C) to 80.6 °F (27.0 °C), though some data centers could operate at higher temperatures.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, cooling at or below 70 °F (21 °C) wastes money and energy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Furthermore, overcooling equipment in environments with a high relative humidity can expose equipment to a high amount of moisture that facilitates the growth of salt deposits on conductive filaments in the circuitry.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A **power and cooling analysis**, also referred to as a thermal assessment, measures the relative temperatures in specific areas as well as the capacity of the cooling systems to handle specific ambient temperatures.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power cooling density is a measure of how much square footage the center can cool at maximum capacity.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The cooling of data centers is the second largest power consumer after servers, with cooling taking about 7% to 30% of energy usage (depending on efficiency), compared to an average of 60% of energy used by servers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] An energy efficiency analysis measures the energy use of data center IT and facilities equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A typical energy efficiency analysis measures factors such as a data center's Power Use Effectiveness (PUE) against industry standards, identifies mechanical and electrical sources of inefficiency, and identifies air-management metrics.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, the limitation of most current metrics and approaches is they do not include IT in the analysis.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Case studies have shown that by addressing energy efficiency holistically in a data center, major efficiencies can be achieved that are not possible otherwise.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Thermal zone mapping uses sensors and computer modeling to create a three-dimensional image of the hot and cool zones in a data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This information can help identify optimal positioning of data center equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For example, critical servers might be placed in a cool zone that is serviced by redundant AC units.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Data centers use a lot of power, consumed via two main usages: the power required to run the equipment and the power required to cool the equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Power efficiency reduces the first category.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Cooling cost reduction through natural means includes location decisions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] When the focus is avoiding good fiber connectivity, power grid connections, and people concentrations to manage the equipment, a data center can be miles away from users.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Mass data centers like Google or Facebook do not need to be near population centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Arctic locations that can use outside air, which provides cooling, are becoming more popular.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Countries with favorable conditions, such as Canada, Finland, Sweden, Norway, and Switzerland are trying to attract cloud computing data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Singapore lifted a three-year ban on new data centers in April 2022.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A major data center hub for the Asia-Pacific region, Singapore lifted its moratorium on new data center projects in 2022, granting four new projects, but rejecting more than 16 data center applications from over 20 received.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] It is very difficult to reuse the heat that comes from air-cooled data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] For this reason, data center infrastructures are more often equipped with heat pumps.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The rapid growth of artificial intelligence (AI) and high-performance computing workloads has increased attention on data center power infrastructure, particularly the relationship between electrical reliability, deployment timelines, energy costs, and decarbonization objectives.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Industry publications have described phased approaches to infrastructure development that enable operators to deploy power capacity rapidly while maintaining pathways toward lower-carbon energy systems as technologies, fuel availability, grid capacity, and economics evolve.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Recent industry discussion has also emphasized "speed-to-power" as a significant consideration in data center development, reflecting the growing importance of securing electrical capacity and resilient power systems within increasingly compressed project timelines.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In the 2020s, the rapid growth of data center construction gave rise to policy debates over tax incentives, electricity grid, water resources, and climate commitments.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] By 2024, at least 36 U.S. states had introduced specific tax incentives aimed at attracting data center investment, most often in the form of sales tax exemptions on servers, networking equipment, and electricity.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Virginia hosts the largest concentration of data centers in the U.S., and a December 2024 audit by its Joint Legislative Audit and Review Commission (JLARC) put the industry's annual contribution at roughly 74,000 jobs and $9.1 billion in gross state product.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The audit reported that the state's sales and use tax exemption was claimed by about 90% of operators and that reduced state revenue by an estimated $928 million in fiscal year 2023.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Thus, JLARC concluded that ending the exemption would likely shrink Virginia's share of new data center investment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Economists have debated the effectiveness of such incentives more broadly.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Further, research by Timothy Bartik of the Upjohn Institute estimated that economic development incentives change firm location decisions in only 2% to 25% of cases.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In response to tax exemption policies, several jurisdictions have started to reevaluate incentives for data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2024, the Georgia General Assembly passed legislation to terminate the state's data center sales tax exemption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] However, the bill was ultimately vetoed by Governor Brian Kemp.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In another case in 2026, the Virginia Senate voted 28 to 12 to phase out the state's data center sales tax exemption as part of broader budget negotiations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Most large data centers use water for evaporative cooling of their servers, and the volumes involved have drawn growing scrutiny.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A 2021 study in *npj Clean Water* estimated that U.S. data centers directly consume about 1.7 billion liters of water per day, with up to 57% of that drawn from potable supplies, and noted that fewer than one-third of operators measured their water use at the time.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] A separate study published in *Environmental Research Letters* found that about one-fifth of direct water use by U.S. data centers came from moderately or highly water-stressed watersheds, and that nearly half of the country's servers ran on electricity drawn from water-stressed regions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] According to a 2024 Berkeley Lab report, data centers in the U.S. had used approximately 17 billion gallons of water.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The same report expected hyperscale data centers specifically to use 16 to 33 billion gallons of water per year by 2028.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In Virginia, the December 2024 JLARC audit reported that data centers in the state consumed about 2.1 billion gallons of water in 2023, an 86% increase since 2019, and that roughly one-third of that came from reclaimed water rather than potable supplies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The audit recommended that local governments be authorized to require water-use estimates as part of the data center permitting process.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] There is no federal U.S. standard requiring data center operators to disclose water consumption, and access to facility-level data has often been limited by non-disclosure agreements (NDAs) with host municipalities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2022, the city of The Dalles, Oregon, settled a public records lawsuit brought by *The Oregonian*, after which Google ended its nationwide practice of treating site-level water use as a trade secret.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2025, several states considered legislation to require data centers to disclose water use, including bills in Virginia, California, and New Jersey, although each was vetoed by the state's governor that year.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The growth of data center electricity demand in the 2020s has prompted regulatory debates over grid capacity, transmission planning, and how the costs of new infrastructure should be allocated among customers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The 2024 Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory (LBNL) report on U.S. data center energy use, prepared at the request of the U.S.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Congress, estimated that data centers accounted for about 4.4% of national electricity consumption in 2023 and projected a rise to between 6.7% and 12% by 2028, depending on growth scenarios.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2025, the IEA projected that data centers would account for nearly half of new U.S. electricity demand growth through 2030.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), the federally designated electric reliability organization for the U.S., identified data centers as the single largest driver of projected demand growth in its 2024 long-term reliability assessment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Additionally, NERC documented a voltage event in the PJM Interconnection region in July 2024, in which roughly 1,500 megawatts of data center load disconnected simultaneously across about 60 facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] How the costs of meeting this demand are shared has also become a central policy question.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The JLARC audit in 2024 estimated that, without any changes to how rates are designed, typical residential customers of Dominion Energy Virginia could see their bills rise by $14 to $37 per month by 2040 because of data center-driven grid investment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] As such, the report recommended creating a separate customer rate class for large data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Some researchers have urged caution in interpreting demand projections.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Furthermore, a 2024 commentary in the journal *Joule* argued that public estimates of future data center electricity use vary widely and that utilities have historically over-forecasted load growth, and called for more transparent data on actual facility-level consumption.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The growth of data centers has raised questions about whether the renewable energy commitments made by their operators are consistent with broader climate goals.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Many large operators report meeting electricity-related emissions targets through annual purchases of renewable energy certificates (RECs) or matching their total annual consumption with renewable generation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2022, a study by *Nature Climate Change* analyzed 115 companies with Science Based Targets.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] It found that about 42% of their reported Scope 2 emissions reductions disappeared once REC-based claims were excluded.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] This directly suggests that some corporate climate progress reflected accounting choices rather than actual reductions in grid emissions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In response, some operators and researchers have proposed 24/7 carbon-free energy matching.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Under this approach, every hour of a facility's electricity use must be matched with carbon-free generation on the same regional grid.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The authors found that annual or volumetric matching did little to cut grid emissions under current U.S. policy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Hourly 24/7 matching cut more, but it cost about $13 to $30 more per megawatt-hour.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] The tension between data center expansion and corporate climate goals has also become apparent in the operators' own disclosures of information.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] In 2024, Google reported its greenhouse gas emissions had risen by about 48% since 2019, attributing the increase in large part to data center electricity use associated with AI workloads.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Similarly, Microsoft reported in 2024 that its emissions had risen by about 29% since 2020, citing the construction and operation of new data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p01] Moreover, the IEA projected in 2025 that global data center carbon dioxide emissions could peak at around 320 million tonnes by 2030 before declining slightly through 2035, with the trajectory depending heavily on the carbon intensity of the electricity supplied to new facilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data centers have significant impacts on local ecologies, politics, and utility infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Political and economic incentives such as tax breaks, land deals, or government subsidies drive data center growth in areas where these incentives are available.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data centers are frequently located in rural areas, where they may displace agriculture.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Growth in the data center industry has prompted several debates about environmental impacts, especially the massive energy and water demands.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The supply chains, emissions, and e-waste also impose significant planetary impacts, raising questions of environmental injustice toward marginalized communities that frequently bear these burdens.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Multiple studies and experts have found that data centers do not bring high-paying jobs to local communities in proportion to the tax subsidies they receive.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The rapid expansion of AI data centers has raised significant concerns over their water consumption, particularly in drought-prone regions.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] According to the IEA, a single 100-megawatt data center, using 2400 MWh of electricity per day, can use up to 2,000,000 litres (530,000 US gal) of water per day.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The electricity use is equivalent to that of 60,000–120,000 households in the U.S., while water use is equivalent about 6,500 households.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Water usage can be divided into three categories: on-site (direct usage from data centers), off-site (indirect usage from electricity), and supply-chain (water usage from manufacturing processes).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] On-site water use refers to the direct water consumed by the data center for the cooling of its equipment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Water is used specifically for space humidification (adding moisture to the air), evaporative cooling systems (cooling air before entering server rooms), and cooling towers (removing heat from the facility).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Off-site water use is the indirect water usage from the electricity generated in data centers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] It is estimated that 56% of U.S. data centers' electricity comes from fossil fuels in thermal power stations, which use water to generate power via steam.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Lastly, data centers consume water through the process of AI chip and server manufacturing.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] These chips, specifically, consume a vast amount of ultrapure water for fabrication and cooling of semiconductor plants.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] While this scope of water usage is not as significant as on-site and off-site water usage, it is still a contributing factor.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Globally, since 2022, more than two-thirds of new data centers have been built in water-stressed areas, including Texas, Arizona, Saudi Arabia, and India, where freshwater scarcity is already a critical issue.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The global water footprint of data centers is estimated at 560 billion litres (150×10^9 US gal) annually, a figure projected to double by 2030 due to increasing AI demand.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In regions like Aragon, Spain, Amazon's planned data centers are licensed to withdraw 755,720 cubic metres (612.67 acre⋅ft) of water per year, sparking conflicts with farmers who rely on the same dwindling supplies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Similar tensions have arisen in Chile, the Netherlands, and Uruguay, where communities protest the diversion of water for tech infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Tech companies, including Microsoft, Google, and Amazon, have pledged to become "water positive" by 2030, aiming to replenish more water than they consume.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] However, critics argue that such commitments often rely on water offsetting, which does not address acute local shortages.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] At least 59 additional data centers are planned for water-stressed U.S. regions by 2028, and AI's global water demand is projected to reach 6.6 billion cubic metres (1,700×10^9 US gal) by 2027.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data centers generate significant electronic waste (e-waste) due to the frequent replacement of hardware such as servers, GPUs, CPUs, memory, and storage devices, often every 2–5 years to meet demands for digital transformation and AI.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Globally, e-waste totaled 62 million metric tons in 2022, with generative AI projected to contribute 1.2 to 5 million metric tons annually by 2030, including valuable metals like copper and gold, and hazardous substances such as lead and mercury.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In the U.S., data centers contribute to an annual loss of $10 billion in discarded e-waste value, including $4 billion in precious metals.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Only 22% of global e-waste is formally collected and recycled, exacerbating environmental pollution and health risks in informal processing sites, often in developing countries where exported waste is handled.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] From a political ecology perspective, data center e-waste highlights power imbalances in resource management and environmental justice, as tech corporations benefit from tax incentives while externalizing costs to marginalized communities through toxic exports and landfill burdens.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where shared resources like metals are depleted without equitable governance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Mitigation strategies include modular hardware designs, secure data erasure for reuse, and extended producer responsibility policies to reduce waste by up to 86% in optimized scenarios.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] According to one 2025 energy model, the U.S. could see energy prices increase 8% nationally by 2030.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Higher electricity prices are already occurring in some regions, particularly those with lots of data centers like Santa Clara, California, and parts of upstate New York.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data centers have also generated concerns in Northern Virginia about whether residents will have to foot the bill for future power lines.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] It has also made it harder to develop housing in London.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] A Bank of America Institute report in July 2024 found that increased demand for electricity due in part to AI has been pushing electricity prices higher and is a significant contributor to electricity inflation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] A Harvard Law School report in March 2025 found that because utilities are increasingly in competition to attract data center contracts from big tech companies, they are likely hiding subsidies to those trillion-dollar companies in power prices by raising costs for American consumers.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data centers have increasingly been analyzed through the lens of political ecology, which explores the intersections of power, politics, and environmental change in technological infrastructure.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Scholars argue that these facilities reshape urban and rural landscapes by existing in marginalized or post-industrial areas, often repurposing abandoned sites while promising economic revitalization through job creation and tax revenues.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] For instance, hyperscale data centers in rural towns like Prineville, Oregon, or Luleå, Sweden, challenge traditional core-periphery dynamics but can exacerbate global inequalities in digital access and resource distribution.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In the context of digital transformation, data centers enable the expansion of cloud computing, AI, and machine learning, but at significant ecological and social costs.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Critics from science and technology studies (STS) highlight how corporate sustainability pledges, such as carbon neutrality targets by companies like Microsoft and Google, often rely on offsets and renewable subsidies that privatize benefits while causing social and environmental harms.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] This ties into debates on the commons, where data centers' intensive use of public resources (like electricity grids and water supplies) represents an enclosure, with tech firms receiving tax breaks and priority access at the expense of local communities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Jobs created by data centers tend to be temporary or few in number.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] A study found the productivity increases enabled by data centers are multiple times larger than gross external damages.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Social mobilizations against data centers help shape the discourse around growth of the industry, raise public awareness of issues data centers present, and may impact public policy.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Groups opposed to new data center projects have expressed concern that digital infrastructure exploits local resources 'to the benefit of actors and institutions residing elsewhere'.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] This may occur when data being processed in a facility belongs to actors in other countries, but local people bear the burdens of water and energy use.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In the U.S., bipartisan community resistance to data center development has grown, with residents voicing concerns about water scarcity, rising utility bills, noise pollution, and urban sprawl.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Facilities in rural areas of the U.S. have been focal points for local resistance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Data Center Watch reported that multiple projects collectively worth $64 billion had been stopped or delayed between May 2024 and March 2025.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] An additional $98 billion worth of projects were blocked or delayed between March and June 2025.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] A Gallup poll taken in March 2026 reported seven out of ten Americans oppose data center projects in their area.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Outside of the U.S., protests in the Netherlands led to a temporary national ban on new mega-centers in 2022.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In Chile, protests by activists to protect water reserves led to Google withdrawing plans to build a data center.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] In the United Kingdom, "March Against the Machines" protests were held.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Residents have been concerned about air, water, and noise pollution, as well as property devaluation, traffic, and the risk of fires.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Other environmental concerns involving AI data centers include e-waste and the embodied energy of construction materials, such as concrete and cement.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] data center, they would orbit above the dawn / dusk transition of the planet.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Housing data centers in space has been proposed for low Earth orbit (LEO).
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The theoretical advantages are that of space-based solar power, in addition to aiding in weather forecasting and weather prediction computation from weather satellites, and the ability to freely scale up.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] However, it is difficult to design cooling systems in space, as convection is not available and sunlight causes large temperature fluctuations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] Other challenges include damage from cosmic rays and micrometeorites.
[src:cloud-security-posture/data-center-p02] The design and shape of data centers could change rapidly in the not-too-distant future with the advent of new technologies, such as quantum computing, biocomputation, and synthetic DNA data storage, as examples.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The **Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program** (**FedRAMP**) is a United States federal government-wide compliance program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The US government describes FedRAMP as FISMA for the cloud.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The FedRAMP PMO mission is to promote the adoption of secure cloud services across the federal government by providing a standardized approach to security and risk assessment.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] Per the OMB memorandum, any cloud services that hold federal data must be FedRAMP authorized.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] FedRAMP prescribes the security requirements and processes that cloud service providers must follow in order for the government to use their service.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] There are two ways to authorize a cloud service through FedRAMP: a Joint Authorization Board (JAB) provisional authorization (P-ATO), and through individual agencies.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] FedRAMP provides accreditation for cloud services for the various cloud offering models which are Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service, (SaaS).
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] Before the introduction of FedRAMP, individual federal agencies managed their own assessment methodologies following guidance set by the Federal Information Security Management Act of 2002.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] FedRAMP is governed by different Executive Branch entities that collaborate to develop, manage, and operate the program.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] There are several laws, mandates, and policies that are foundational to FedRAMP.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] FISMA–the Federal Information Security Modernization Act–requires that agencies authorize the information systems that they use.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The FedRAMP Policy Memo requires federal agencies to use FedRAMP when assessing, authorizing, and continuously monitoring cloud services in order to aid agencies in the authorization process as well as save government resources and eliminate duplicative efforts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] FedRAMP's security baselines are derived from NIST SP 800-53 (as revised) with a set of control enhancements that pertain to the unique security requirements of cloud computing.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] Accredited by the American Association for Laboratory Accreditation (A2LA), these assessment organizations must demonstrate independence and the technical competence required to test security implementations and collect representative evidence.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The FedRAMP Marketplace provides a searchable, sortable database of Cloud Service Offerings (CSOs) that have achieved a FedRAMP designation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] 3PAOs, accredited auditors that can perform the FedRAMP assessment, are listed within the Marketplace.
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] The FedRAMP Marketplace is maintained by the FedRAMP Program Management Office (PMO).
[src:cloud-security-posture/fedramp] A 2026 ProPublica investigation found that FedRAMP entered into a partnership with Microsoft despite considerable concerns about the security of its cloud technology.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The concept of managing infrastructure through code emerged from early configuration management practices.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] In the 1990s, tools such as CFEngine, created by Mark Burgess in 1993, introduced the idea of describing system configuration in a declarative language rather than executing manual commands, laying the intellectual groundwork for IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] IaC emerged as organizations began managing larger and more complex infrastructure, particularly with the growth of cloud computing and the need to provision resources consistently and at scale.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Treating infrastructure configuration like software - storing it in version control, reviewing it, and deploying it automatically allowed teams to reduce manual errors and reproduce environments reliably.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The ability to treat infrastructure as code and use the same tools as any other software project would allow developers to rapidly deploy applications.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The value of IaC can be broken down into three measurable categories: cost, speed, and risk.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Cost reduction aims at helping not only the enterprise financially, but also in terms of people and effort, meaning that by removing the manual component, organizations are able to refocus their efforts on other enterprise tasks.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure automation enables speed through faster execution when configuring your infrastructure and provides visibility to help other teams across the enterprise work quickly and more efficiently.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Automation removes the risk associated with human error, like manual misconfiguration; removing this can decrease downtime and increase reliability.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] These outcomes and attributes help the enterprise move toward implementing a culture of DevOps: the combined work of development and operations.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] There are generally two approaches to IaC: declarative (functional) vs. imperative (procedural).
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The difference between the declarative and the imperative approach is essentially *what* versus *how*.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach focuses on what the eventual target configuration should be; the imperative focuses on how the infrastructure is to be changed to meet this.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The declarative approach defines the desired state and the system executes what needs to happen to achieve that desired state.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Imperative defines specific commands that need to be executed in the appropriate order to end with the desired conclusion.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Infrastructure as Code (IaC) allows organizations to manage servers and their configurations using code.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] There are two ways to apply these configurations to servers: the 'push' and 'pull' methods.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'push' method, the system controlling the configuration directly sends instructions to the server.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] In the 'pull' method, the server retrieves its own instructions from the controlling system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] There are many tools that fulfill infrastructure automation capabilities and use IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Broadly speaking, any framework or tool that performs changes or configures infrastructure declaratively or imperatively based on a programmatic approach can be considered IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Traditionally, server (lifecycle) automation and configuration management tools were used to accomplish IaC.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Now enterprises are also using continuous configuration automation tools or stand-alone IaC frameworks, such as Microsoft’s PowerShell DSC or AWS CloudFormation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] All continuous configuration automation (CCA) tools can be thought of as extensions of traditional IaC frameworks.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] They leverage IaC to change, configure, and automate infrastructure, and they also provide visibility, efficiency, and flexibility in how infrastructure is managed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] These additional attributes provide enterprise-level security and compliance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Community content is a key determinant of an open-source CCA tool's quality.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] According to Gartner, the value of CCA tools is "as dependent on user-community-contributed content and support as it is on the commercial maturity and performance of the automation tooling".
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Established vendors such as Puppet and Chef have created their own communities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Chef has Chef Community Repository and Puppet has PuppetForge.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Other vendors rely on adjacent communities and leverage other IaC frameworks such as PowerShell DSC.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] New vendors are emerging that are not content-driven, but model-driven with the intelligence in the product to deliver content.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] These visual, object-oriented systems work well for developers, but they are especially useful to production-oriented DevOps and operations constituents that value models versus scripting for content.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] As the field continues to develop and change, the community-based content will become ever more important to how IaC tools are used, unless they are model-driven and object-oriented.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Other tools include AWS CloudFormation, cdist, StackStorm, Juju, and Step CI.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] IaC can be a key attribute of enabling best practices in DevOps.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Developers become more involved in defining configuration and Ops teams get involved earlier in the development process.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Tools that utilize IaC bring visibility to the state and configuration of servers and ultimately provide the visibility to users within the enterprise, which brings teams together to maximize their efforts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Automation in general aims to take the confusion and error-prone aspect of manual processes and make it more efficient, and productive.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Allowing for better software and applications to be created with flexibility, less downtime, and an overall cost-effective way for the company.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] IaC is intended to reduce the complexity that kills efficiency out of manual configuration.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] Automation and collaboration are considered central points in DevOps; infrastructure automation tools are often included as components of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:cloud-security-posture/infrastructure-as-code] The 2020 Cloud Threat Report released by Unit 42 (the threat intelligence unit of cybersecurity provider Palo Alto Networks) identified around 200,000 potential vulnerabilities in infrastructure-as-code templates.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In computing, a **virtual machine** (**VM**) is the virtualization or emulation of a computer system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are based on computer architectures and provide the functionality of a physical computer.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Their implementations may involve specialized hardware, software, or a combination of the two.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Some virtual machine emulators, such as QEMU and video game console emulators, are designed to also emulate (or "virtually imitate") different system architectures, thus allowing execution of software applications and operating systems written for another CPU or architecture.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] OS-level virtualization allows the resources of a computer to be partitioned via the kernel.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The terms are not universally interchangeable.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A 'virtual machine' was originally defined by Popek and Goldberg as "an efficient, isolated duplicate of a real computer machine." Current use includes virtual machines that have no direct correspondence to any real hardware.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The physical, "real-world" hardware running the VM is generally referred to as the 'host', and the virtual machine emulated on that machine is generally referred to as the 'guest'.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A host can emulate several guests, each of which can emulate different operating systems and hardware platforms.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The desire to run multiple operating systems was the initial motive for virtual machines, so as to allow time-sharing among several single-tasking operating systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In some respects, a system virtual machine can be considered a generalization of the concept of virtual memory that historically preceded it.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] IBM's CP/CMS, the first systems to allow full virtualization, implemented time sharing by providing each user with a single-user operating system, the Conversational Monitor System (CMS).
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Unlike virtual memory, a system virtual machine entitled the user to write privileged instructions in their code.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This approach had certain advantages, such as adding input/output devices not allowed by the standard system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] As technology evolves virtual memory for purposes of virtualization, new systems of memory overcommitment may be applied to manage memory sharing among multiple virtual machines on one computer operating system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] It may be possible to share *memory pages* that have identical contents among multiple virtual machines that run on the same physical machine, what may result in mapping them to the same physical page by a technique termed kernel same-page merging (KSM).
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This is especially useful for read-only pages, such as those holding code segments, which is the case for multiple virtual machines running the same or similar software, software libraries, web servers, middleware components, etc.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The guest operating systems do not need to be compliant with the host hardware, thus making it possible to run different operating systems on the same computer (e.g., Windows, Linux, or prior versions of an operating system) to support future software.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The use of virtual machines to support separate guest operating systems is popular in regard to embedded systems.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A typical use would be to run a real-time operating system simultaneously with a preferred complex operating system, such as Linux or Windows.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Another use would be for novel and unproven software still in the developmental stage, so it runs inside a sandbox.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Virtual machines have other advantages for operating system development and may include improved debugging access and faster reboots.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Multiple VMs running their own guest operating system are frequently engaged for server consolidation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A **process virtual machine**, sometimes called an *application virtual machine*, or *Managed Runtime Environment* (MRE), runs as a normal application inside a host OS and supports a single process.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] It is created when that process is started and deleted when it is closed.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Its purpose is to provide a platform-independent programming environment that abstracts away details of the underlying hardware or operating system and allows a program to execute in the same way on any platform.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A process VM provides a high-level abstraction – that of a high-level programming language (compared to the low-level ISA abstraction of the system VM).
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Process VMs are implemented using an interpreter; performance comparable to compiled programming languages can be achieved by the use of just-in-time compilation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This type of VM has become popular with the Java programming language, which is implemented using the Java virtual machine.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Other examples include the Parrot virtual machine and the .NET Framework, which runs on a VM called the Common Language Runtime.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] All of them can serve as an abstraction layer for any computer language.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A special case of process VMs are systems that abstract over the communication mechanisms of a (potentially heterogeneous) computer cluster.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Such a VM does not consist of a single process, but one process per physical machine in the cluster.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] They are designed to ease the task of programming concurrent applications by letting the programmer focus on algorithms rather than the communication mechanisms provided by the interconnect and the OS.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] They do not hide the fact that communication takes place, and as such do not attempt to present the cluster as a single machine.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Unlike other process VMs, these systems do not provide a specific programming language, but are embedded in an existing language; typically such a system provides bindings for several languages (e.g., C and Fortran).
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Examples are Parallel Virtual Machine (PVM) and Message Passing Interface (MPI).
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Both system virtual machines and process virtual machines date to the 1960s and remain areas of active development.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Significant advances occurred in the implementation of Smalltalk-80, particularly the Deutsch/Schiffmann implementation which pushed just-in-time (JIT) compilation forward as an implementation approach that uses process virtual machine.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Later notable Smalltalk VMs were VisualWorks, the Squeak Virtual Machine, and Strongtalk.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A related language that produced a lot of virtual machine innovation was the Self programming language, which pioneered adaptive optimization and generational garbage collection.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] These techniques proved commercially successful in 1999 in the HotSpot Java virtual machine.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Other innovations include a register-based virtual machine, to better match the underlying hardware, rather than a stack-based virtual machine, which is a closer match for the programming language; in 1995, this was pioneered by the Dis virtual machine for the Limbo language.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In full virtualization, the virtual machine simulates enough hardware to allow an unmodified "guest" OS (one designed for the same instruction set) to be run in isolation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In hardware-assisted virtualization, the hardware provides architectural support that facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system offered by IBM as an official product.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD provided additional hardware to support virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Sun Microsystems (acquired by Oracle Corporation) added similar features in their UltraSPARC T-Series processors in 2005.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Examples of virtualization platforms adapted to such hardware include KVM, VMware Workstation, VMware Fusion, Hyper-V, Windows Virtual PC, Xen, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Oracle VM Server for SPARC, VirtualBox and Parallels Workstation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In 2006, first-generation 32- and 64-bit x86 hardware support was found to rarely offer performance advantages over software virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In OS-level virtualization, a physical server is virtualized at the operating system level, enabling multiple isolated and secure virtualized servers to run on a single physical server.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The "guest" operating system environments share the same running instance of the operating system as the host system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Thus, the same operating system kernel is also used to implement the "guest" environments, and applications running in a given "guest" environment view it as a stand-alone system.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The pioneer implementation was FreeBSD jails; other examples include Docker, Solaris Containers, OpenVZ, Linux-VServer, LXC, AIX Workload Partitions, Parallels Virtuozzo Containers, and iCore Virtual Accounts.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A *snapshot* is a state of a virtual machine, and generally its storage devices, at an exact point in time.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] A snapshot enables the virtual machine's state at the time of the snapshot to be restored later, effectively undoing any changes that occurred afterwards.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This capability is useful as a backup technique, for example, prior to performing a risky operation.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Virtual machines frequently use virtual disks for their storage; in a very simple example, a 10-gigabyte hard disk drive is simulated with a 10-gigabyte flat file.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Any requests by the VM for a location on its physical disk are transparently translated into an operation on the corresponding file.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Once such a translation layer is present, however, it is possible to intercept the operations and send them to different files, depending on various criteria.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Every time a snapshot is taken, a new file is created, and used as an overlay for its predecessors.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] New data is written to the topmost overlay; reading existing data, however, needs the overlay hierarchy to be scanned, resulting in accessing the most recent version.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Thus, the entire stack of snapshots is virtually a single coherent disk; in that sense, creating snapshots works similarly to the incremental backup technique.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Other components of a virtual machine can also be included in a snapshot, such as the contents of its random-access memory (RAM), BIOS settings, or its configuration settings.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] "Save state" feature in video game console emulators is an example of such snapshots.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Restoring a snapshot consists of discarding or disregarding all overlay layers that are added after that snapshot, and directing all new changes to a new overlay.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The snapshots described above can be moved to another host machine with its own hypervisor; when the VM is temporarily stopped, snapshotted, moved, and then resumed on the new host, this is known as migration.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] If the older snapshots are kept in sync regularly, this operation can be quite fast, and allow the VM to provide uninterrupted service while its prior physical host is, for example, taken down for physical maintenance.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Similar to the migration mechanism described above, failover allows the VM to continue operations if the host fails.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Generally it occurs if the migration has stopped working.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] However, in this case, the VM continues operation from the *last-known* coherent state, rather than the *current* state, based on whatever materials the backup server was last provided with.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Nested virtualization refers to the ability of running a virtual machine within another, having this general concept extendable to an arbitrary depth.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] In other words, nested virtualization refers to running one or more hypervisors inside another hypervisor.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The nature of a nested guest virtual machine does not need to be homogeneous with its host virtual machine; for example, application virtualization can be deployed within a virtual machine created by using hardware virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Furthermore, moving already existing virtualized environments into a cloud, following the Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) approach, is much more complicated if the destination IaaS platform does not support nested virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] The way nested virtualization can be implemented on a particular computer architecture depends on supported hardware-assisted virtualization capabilities.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] If a particular architecture does not provide hardware support required for nested virtualization, various software techniques are employed to enable it.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Over time, more architectures gain required hardware support; for example, since the Haswell microarchitecture (announced in 2013), Intel started to include VMCS shadowing as a technology that accelerates nested virtualization.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] Virtual machines are frequently used to isolate applications from one another for security.
[src:cloud-security-posture/virtual-machine] This architectural design (used by Qubes OS, Whonix, KickSecure, and Dangerzone) can prevent the spread of malware from one compromised system (e.g. an email client opening an infected document) to another system (e.g. a password manager).
